segments.text: key campus leaders, deans and faculty members and so forth in the late 40s and early 50s?
Well, Mr. D.W. Williams was chairman of the Athletic Council and I remember going to LSU one time with Bones Irving.
Bones had forgotten to make a reservation for the football team and Mr. Williams was waiting for Bones to get there and he said, you never confirmed the reservations.
But Mr. Penberthy followed as chairman of the Athletic Council and was very active.
And was the council an important organization for athletics?
Yes.
Chris Grinman.
Dr. Chris Grinman was chairman of the Athletic Council when Bear Bryant came.
Was he already the department head in industrial ed by then?
I think he was by that time, yes.
What about the deans?
Who were they?
Well, let me think a minute.
The dean of agriculture was Dr. Shepardson.
Charles Shepardson later became a member of the board of the Federal Fair Bank.
He was head of the Dairy Science Department.
Dean Kyle, back in the early days, when I first came back.
No, he'd already been gone by then.
When I was a student, Dean Kyle would be back in Washington.
And one of these, somewhere around here, signed by Dean Kyle.
Engineering, of course, was Gilchrist, followed by Bolton, Dean Bolton, Dean of Engineering, Gilchrist, Dean of Engineering.
Agriculture was
Patterson, R.E.
Patterson.
Arts and Sciences.
Arts and Sciences.
Early as a student, Dean T.D.
Brooks.
And later, when Earl came in, Brother Frank Hewitt.
Before him.
Before him.
Wait a second.
Abbott.
Dr. John Paul Abbott.
Dr. Abbott.
In Vet Medicine.
In Vet Medicine.
was back in the early days, was Dean about Ohio State as Dean Armstead.
Price.
Slick out and was in the late 50s.
Yeah, and the one back prior to him was Armstead and Bouton.
Dean Bouton was an Ohio State graduate, a good man, salty, tough.
And prior to somebody there was Dean Marshdown.
As far as you were aware, if there was a tug of war between the deans, who had the most influence?
Which of the schools?
Well, there was a tug of war between agriculture and all the rest of it.
The Department of Agriculture always felt like they were mistreated.
And they were working.
And they were.
it worked to try to get their share of everything.
Now did the others feel that agriculture was getting more than its share?
I suspect so.
I suspect so, though I never heard anyone just come out and say so.
But, well, Vincent, of course, was an engineer.
You know, some of the schools I think really were mistreated, like the school of veterinary medicine.
I think they were terribly mistreated.
I think Dean Hubert made a wonderful dean, Dean Franklin.
Before we get to him, let's move up and bring this man Rudder here.
Okay.
Did you know who Rudder was?
Absolutely.
Okay.
Earl Rutter was living in Brady.
He owned a drug store with his brother.
He was working as a vice president of an aviation company in Brady that were manufacturing wings as a subcontractor for some aircraft factory.
I can't tell you who it was, what airplane it was.
My father had
contracted to sell some land up in Hunt County under the Texas Veterans Land Program, Baskin-Gines.
And that contract had been going for six months or eight months and never put here anything.
Earl Rudder had been on our executive board of our association.
Earl Rudder had been on our council.
And
Earl Rutter talked to me many hours about A&M and the relationship at the time between the so-called system officers and the university officers.
And that there was a serious conflict.
And Earl was just as pure in heart as any person you could ever find.
He served as mayor, didn't he?
He served as mayor of Brady for six or eight years.
He was also Lyndon Johnson's campaign manager in West Texas, where Colt Stevenson had been for years and years and years.
But Burrell served as Lyndon's campaign manager, did a real good job for him.
When Bascom Giles was convicted or was indicted or whatever, Earl Rudder went to Austin to see Alan Shivers.
There was a man from Brady that Earl wanted to recommend to the governor to be appointed as Land Commissioner for the state of Texas.
And Earl went into Governor Shivers office and made his speech.
And Alan Shivers listened to the speech.
And when it was over, Alan says, I'm not going to appoint your man to this position.
I'm going to appoint you.
And did so.
And I had known Earl very well up to that point.
And the first day at his office, I called Earl and said, can I come see you?
He said, sure, come on down.
And I drove down there to talk to him about my father's business, his farms that he'd contract to sell.
But anyway, I visited him.
He got it all straightened out pretty quick.
I don't remember what years he served as Land Commissioner, but I know he came to end.
Let me say this, my father died in 54.
He died before the launch was sold.
So, sometime I think about in 54, probably Earl went to Austin, maybe 55.
He served as land commissioner until the fall of 57 when the board went to Austin and talked him into coming up here as vice president, laying him under Tom Harrington.
Now, can you identify who or whom was it, may have been more than one, who kind of said, Rudder is the person we want?
Let me think.
I can't do that.
You're also indicating by your lack of mentioning of it that there wasn't some former student who went to the board or there wasn't a campaign for him that they sat down and thought, who do we want?
Let me say this, that in those years, let's say 51 to 57, Earl was very active in the association.
And he was very closely associated with people like Harold Dunn, Rufus Peoples.
People who were both very active in the association and
say on the Board of Directors, and Polly Krueger, and Rufus Peoples, and Harold Dunn.
And so, when we got to the point where we needed somebody to take over the administration of this institution, we needed that.
We needed that.
I think
The impetus, if I had to name somebody, would be Harold.
What was not happening here then?
Instead of saying what was going wrong, I'll say what wasn't happening.
We had no continuity of leadership.
We had had president after president after president.
And we had the presidents that we had were acting or temporary or not here for long.
And they were just people that...
did not want to run the risk of fighting the system or changing the system or creating problems that would be detrimental to their well-being.
And so just nothing got done.
I think primarily they wouldn't face up to the realities of life with the court and the non-coeducation.
All right.
David Morgan came as president as an outsider.
David Morgan came as a total outsider from Colorado.
And David Morgan tried to do the best he could.
But that was at a point when I guess our enrollment was at the lowest that has been almost in the history of this institution.
I think in 1953,
Our enrollment total was 53 students.
Now, was he a capable man?
Yes.
That's what I've heard from others.
He was a very capable man.
His problem, nobody's listening, was his wife.
Now, I thought David Morgan was a fine fella and he was a good administrator.
He attempted to do things, but once Tom Harrington named him president, Tom was chancellor, Tom would keep knocking him down and interfering and not letting him go on his own to do things.
His problem was his wife.
They were living in the old president's home.
before it burned.
And his wife would go over his head and over the head of the chancellor who was Tom Perry and go to the board members individually and complain about what was happening.
And you can understand what a terrible problem that created.
Now almost every board member in that era was a former student?
I think so.
Okay.
And so was he terminated or did he resign?
I think he was terminated because I had no actual fact on that.
So Earl Rutter is brought here as executive vice president or?
Vice president or executive vice president, I'm not sure of the title.
As far as you know, was it pretty clearly understood that he was going to become the president?
Yes.
It was him, he and I talked about that group.
And he said, I came to be president, they wouldn't give me the title.
And he said, I am vice president.
But he was placed in the office of Dave Martins and the co-governor.
And he, I'm talking about early on.
He would talk to me and said, well, they just don't do anything.
In the meantime, while he was vice president, the bunch up at the chancellor's office were trying to pull everything away from me and him.
He was in the chancellor's position.
Sounds very familiar.
And here was Tom Harrington.
Here was E.L. Angel, Lionel Angel.
Here was Henderson Shuffler.
Here was Clyde Freeman.
Here was John Calhoun.
Just trying to pull it all away.
Extension service and the whole thing.
Just grabbing, grabbing, grabbing.
All right.
And you say that you chatted with Mr. Rutter a lot.
Yeah.
Did he ever give you any feeling that he worried about whether or not he could relate to the academics?
Yes.
The academic people.
Yes, he did.
He worried that he would not be accepted by the academic life on the campus.
And he talked to me about that.
And I said, Earl, if you'll be honest and forthright and try not to be something that you're not, use your main strengths and don't worry about your weaknesses, if they're weaknesses.
I said, you're a good administrator.
You know how to operate in legislative circles.
You know how to operate with the big people of Texas.
And I said, you do that.
You do that.
Because he was an old acquaintance of Johnson and Connolly and key legislators.
Yes.
Yes.
And at that time, the University of Texas had very weak people, like Branson.
And they did not know very well in Austin how to deal with the legislature.
You'd know they were sitting right there with them.
But Earl did.
And they depended on Earl to help them with certain legislative problems.
And Earl was very good at that.
But Earl constantly worried about the fact that he had no advanced degrees.
That he was not an educator.
He wasn't a glib speaker.
He was not a good speaker at all.
And he knew that.
And he knew that.
He had no timetable.
He'd get up to make speech and if somebody wouldn't tug on him or be in the back of the room and say this, he would talk for an hour and a half.
And so he was not the speaker that, well, Dave Market, Tom Harrington, certainly Jack Wood, all outstanding speakers, Earl just didn't have that aspect of him.
Where did the idea for what would later be called the Century Study, where did that originate?
Let me explain to you.
A lot of people are claiming credit
You'll find this in your studies, or co-education, auction on post.
A lot of people claim it's crazy.
Let me tell you exactly the honest truth of what happened.
In the early 60s, our board, I'm talking about the association board, said we want to do a long-range study
of where this association's going and where it needs to be in 25 or 30 years.
So our board and our officers appointed what we call the Long Range Committee.
And they met and they did a hell of a job.
We talked to them.
We developed the Distinguished Achievement Award
Faculty Distinguished Achievement Awards was right there.
That was developed in that study.
Distinguished Alumni Awards developed right there in that study.
The convocations, the computer, conversion to computer records, and the more we talked, the more we realized,
We can't finish this job until we know where the university itself is going.
Because our number one function is to help that university get where it wants to go.
And right now, they don't know where they want to go.
Nobody has put the light out there for them to guide them.
So we did our study.
And Mr.
Harold Dunn, Tyree Bell, said, we have to have a meeting with the Board of Regents and the Board of Directors of Maine.
We want Earl Rudder to be there.
Well, Earl Rudder didn't want any of this stuff.
He wasn't ready for that, was he?
So I said, okay, what do you want us to do?
Jimmy Astin was President of the Association, one of the strongest guys I ever met.
I said, let's, and he said, we're going to have a meeting.
This was Jimmy Astin.
He said, we're going to have a meeting of the Board of Regents of A&M.
We're going to meet in the Carousel Club.
in the Sheridan Hotel in Dallas.
And we were going to line it up.
So we lined up a date and an evening.
The Republic National Bank handled the cost of the meeting.
And I remember Tyree and Harold Dunn and Jimmy Astin were our three representatives.
Of course, I was there.
Pearl was there.
And those three men laid out the probe.
And they said, we cannot finish our study until A&M has its own study.
We want you to tell us where you want to go and what you want to do, what you want to accomplish.
By 1976, our 100th birthday.
We talked about it.
Earl didn't say much.
But the board talked about it.
They said, we think you're right.
We think it ought to be done.
And we'll get started.
And we put up, I believe it was $75,000.
It might have been $50,000 or $75,000 to finance this.
A lot of money then.
A lot of money.
I attended another meeting.
They agreed to do it.
I attended another meeting with some of the members of the board up in the old boardroom, which was in Duncan Hall, upstairs there.

And when we started talking about how we were going to set it up, who were going to be appointed, and so forth, we said, well, since we decided to call it the century stuff, and we decided to name about 100
because it was the century and because we were looking to be 100th birthday of the institution.
100 outstanding Texans.
And we agreed not to confine it to any people.
So we did, I don't remember what the breakup was, but it was somewhere around 50-50 or maybe 60-40, something like that.
We had a lot of outstanding Texans, like Adam Shivers,
and others on it that were not in and graduates from Houston, Texas.
And it was this study, and this study alone, that prompted the appointment of the Aspirations Committee, which you hear Ray Bowen quoting from from time to time.
It was not the Committee of Aspirations.
It was a century report that prompted
The Corps being named voluntary so that you could take your pick, go in the Corps or not go in the Corps.
And name change.
What about racial integration?
Racial integration.
And this other thing was seeking out outstanding faculty people.
Were there any particularly strong advocates of these, of this idea of a century study?
You mentioned Dunn and Aston and Tyree Bell and Polly Krueger and Louis Bloodworth were all very, George Morgan,
Beaumont, our association was really strong for them.
I mean to a man, they all wanted him.
Now, there were some that were not happy with the outcome of it, but you know, we talked about that, Charlie Babcock, some of the other clubs, and the Smith, Mr. Travis Smith,
But by and large, the association was strong for it.
Earl was not real happy with it.
I'll tell you what I think why he wasn't.
When Earl came here, there was a lot to be done.
And in fairness to Earl, he had his boat loaded.
But he did need guidance.
And of course, I guess he'd get guidance from everybody
Whether he wanted it or not.
Whether he wanted it or not.
But Earl realized that some of the stud horses were on this other side and were talking co-education, were talking optional code, and were breaking some of these traditions that were hurting us.
And once he saw that the real big boys were just insisting on it, he decided to go with it.
But still, even during all the studies, he held back on name change.
He didn't want the name change.
He was afraid that the change of the name would cause A&M to lose some of its standing, whatever standing it had.
All right, one day on that one, one day in 1970, about a month before he got sick, I was in his office and he knew that I had been the secretary who had drafted the aspirations report.
He said, if you guys had recommended the name LSU has, it would have passed.
And I said, what?
And he said, the name over there is the Louisiana State University and Agricultural and Mechanical College.
And he said, us old guys didn't want to lose the A&M.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Were there a number of others who felt that way?
Not particularly.
Oh, okay.
Not particularly.
Who was it?
Somebody told me that, who came up with that name?
I don't know what it was.
Maggie McGee was big in those days.
Yes, yes.
Maggie McGee is more responsible for anybody else for this whole thing.
higher education in Texas been?
Do you remember when we used to go around the state in his airplane and make speeches?
So Maggie was very involved in this century study.
Somebody suggested at a meeting one time, not an A&M graduate, just name it Texas A&M University and be done with it.
And that's what happened.
All right, so there was a former student
leadership recommended that there be a study of what A&M ought to be on its centennial.
It was then called the Century Study.
Then there were different parts of it.
I ended up being on the Aspirations Committee.
We were surprised when we voted as a committee on those special points that the vote was unanimous on every point.
We thought, each of us thought we were the only one.
We were not aware that the former student's leadership had a number of people who agreed.
So that if somebody ever interviewed me about what was former student pressure on us, there was none.
Okay, I've heard that the board of directors then
as they were getting ready to consider, that they were hoping that the association leadership would endorse it.
Share that with me.
All right.
I had left by then.
That was in 64.
Okay.
And I left in the fall of 64, early in the fall of 64.
And John Lindsay was president of the association.
Buck Weiss had been named to take my place.
And Earl had asked John if the association would pass a resolution in support of this committee, namely in support of everything that was done, including co-education and optional court.
So they drafted the resolution, passed it, and adjourned the meeting.
I've heard that that was the last item.
Excuse me, I want to try to hear something.
Sure.
I'll be sure to answer that phone.
All right.
On the century study and so forth, the board of directors then, were you all aware of what their feelings were?
Were they positive or negative about
these changes or did you know?
I don't think I knew.
I don't think I knew.

I know that when the thing was over and they were attempting to get the thing written and I know several drafts were prepared and I don't think there was a lot of approval of that draft and I think that's probably when you came into the picture.
By that time, my main contact with the work of the Century Council was through Earl and through Wayne Hall and Dorsey.
And we brought this guy, or they brought this guy,
Bob Hunt, who was a farce.
He was kind of the supposed executive director or something.
He was the executive director of the century.
